[Student "S"]
{You could either use a transfer or you could jump to 3\S. You decide on the transfer and bid 2\H. Partner jumps to 3\S!  

You could either use a transfer or you could jump to 3\S. You decide on the transfer and bid 2\H. Partner jumps to 3\S! 

The 3\S bid is a "Super-accept", showing a maximum 1NT opener, 4 \Ss and a doubleton. In other words, partner's hand has revalued to 18 points. So you bid 6\S (or you could ask for Aces instead).

The contract would be 6\S played by North.

South plays 6\S. West leads the \CQ, East follows with the \C2.

You win the first trick with the \CA in your hand.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = 2

There are two obvious possibilities for avoiding the \H loser. You could finesse East for the \HK; this is a 50% chance. The \Ds could split 3-3; this is a 36% chance.

In fact, your chances are better than either of those percentages because you can try the \Ds first, and if they <b>DON'T</b> split you can then try the \H finesse. 

Pull trumps; West shows up with 3 trumps. Play the \DK, then a small \D to dummy's \DA. On this trick West follows with the \D10.  

Your contract just became a sure thing! Play the \CK to strip both your hands of \Cs. Lead dummy's last \D,  and when East plays low, finesse the \D9. If the finesse wins, discard a \H from dummy on your good \D. But if the finesse loses to West's \DJ, he will be endplayed and have to lead a \H into your \H A Q or give you a ruff/sluff with a \C. And on top of that your fourth \D will be good. 

In this actual Deal your \D finesse worked which gave you 4 \D tricks.

But imagine that the \DJ is transposed to the West hand. He wins that \D trick but must give you the contract with his return.}
[Play "W"]CQ

